"an oily suspension of chloramphenicol is effective against meningococcal meningitis. 112 This is consequently the antibiotic of choice in an epidemic. A single injection is certainly preferable to ampicillin, which requires several injections a day and costs ten times more than treatment with chloramphenicol. On the other hand, chloramphenicol is not very effective against other forms of bacterial meningitis (H. influenzae, streptococcus, pneumococcus, etc.). 113 Before a treatment regimen can be decided, then, bacteriological confirmation of the germ's identity is necessary. \n# Organization of Care\nUsing the short-term treatment makes handling a large number of cases possible; but hospitalization is usually necessary."